metadata.name: Bonsai Bonanza #230
metadata.description:
In previous works, I was attracted by the idea of ​​the domestication of plants.
According to Wikipedia, the purposes of bonsai are primarily contemplation for the viewer, and the pleasant exercise of effort and ingenuity for the grower. By contrast with other plant cultivation practices, bonsai is not intended for production of food or for medicine. Instead, bonsai practice focuses on long-term cultivation and shaping of one or more small trees growing in a container.
I pressume that the main intention is aesthetic. The beauty. Because we love beautiful things.
It is very interesting how we modify certain creatures for our sake of satisfaction.

May this collection brings you good fortune.

metadata.name: ylb-mess-A #282
metadata.description:
With colors and shapes reminiscent of childhood LEGO explorations, 'ylb-mess-A' explores the assembly process in reverse, using recursive subdivision to create detailed structures instead of progressively building a complex structure brick by brick. Although the tools I use to explore and create have changed over the years, this piece reminds me of the natural creative curiosity that was instilled in me at an early age, for which I am incredibly grateful.

metadata.name: Alleles #39
metadata.description:
An allele, short for 'allelomorph', is an alternative version of a specific gene.

This collection (which is in no way scientifically accurate), was born out of an exercise in simplicity. Outputs are made up of arrangements of squares in various compositions, yet within that we are free to imagine what they could mean. For some, the resulting shapes might represent DNA strands or atoms. Others might see cells or the building blocks of the hereditary instructions that shape us as individuals. 

A generative genetic report accompanies each output to spark the imagination and attempt to attach further meaning to each composition. Some gene sequences carry mutations, however not all mutations are visually apparent. Please refer to the fxhash features to view the reports accordingly.

Texture is used subtly, so for maximum enjoyment it is recommended that you save and view your outputs at full size in order to best enjoy the details.

Press 'S' to save a 2400 x 3396 px PNG file.

attributes.name: Genetic Profile
attributes.value: Exploration of the genetic information presented suggests subject may experience rare occurences of emotional outbursts and lack of assertiveness, yet also shows above average [REDACTED] and kindness. Maximum potential hereditary height (excluding nutritional and environmental factors) is estimated at 204-210cm. Projected natural lifespan estimated at 105-109 years. Additional presence of mutated markers requires regular tests and observation to asses the viability of the subject as a candidate for programs for the enhanced. Particular attention should be drawn to markers 338 through 585, as these may indicate the presence of molecular permeability and or enhanced strength.

metadata.name: Sharding #46
metadata.description:
A virtual gallery displays sculptural forms that slowly get fractured into shards by falling coins.

Summer, 2022 I had 2 (physical) art exhibitions in Santa Fe, New Mexico. Both exhibitions combined physical and digital work, including NFT's. During the exhibition period, I was struck by the spatial and temporal limitations of the physical galleries, not to mention the elitist economic model. This experience was in stark contrast to the very positive, even joyful, experience I've been having publishing NFT's, especially on fxHash.

'Sharding' explores the creation and destruction of generative knot, and related, geometries. The facetted geometry is creating utilizing the following steps:
1. curve creation
2. form extrusion
3. Verlet node creation
4. facetted face creation

The different steps enable the forms to be disassembled/reassembled into their face primitives, including accurate (enough) collision response.

Interactivity:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
Mouse Rt Btn -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
r: reassemble geometry
w: toggle wireframe on/off
-: reduce active coins
+: increase active coins
p: screen capture

Note:
Please post your favorite 'Sharding' screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

Thank you Paul Bourke, for some of the knot equations

metadata.name: Metropolis IX #36
metadata.description:
We divide spaces into smaller spaces which we conquer and live in our solitude. We call that Metropolis.

Started this piece as a rule based generative art. Simply the algorithm takes a rectangle and throws 2 random points inside it within defined x and y distances. Then using those 2 points, algorithm draws another rectangle and assigns letters to the corners of rectangle "A,B,C,D" starting from top left corner in clockwise direction. Then it starts to draw cells from inner rectangle's corner A to parent's corner A and goes on. Once 4 cells are created, it creates 4 more cells in between other cells, thus dividing a rectangle into 9 pieces. This is where "IX" comes from. Depending on the cell properties; algorithm assigns circles, triangles, lines and points to cells creating a city scape when certain parameters are given to the division algorithm.

There are 18 possible outcomes:
"Hazy Day" 13% probability (half of this style will come with slightly more color transition)
"Hazy Night" 10% probability
"Crystal Day" 11% probability
"Crystal Night" 5% probability
"Mondrian Day"  3% probability
"Mondrian Night" 3% probability
"Bauhaus Day" 3% probability
"Bauhaus Night" 3% probability
"1 Chroma Day" 4% probability (Multiple values of a single hue on a monochrome gradient)
"Mondrian Crystal Day" 3% probability
"Mondrian Crystal Night" 3% probability
"Monochrome Day" 3% probability 
"Monochrome Night" 4% probability 
"Vibrant Day" 12% probability
"Vibrant Night" 9% probability
"Rainbow Day' 5% probability
"Rainbow Night' 3% probability
"Chaotic Day"   3% probability (which takes pretty random parameters and 25% of this outcome has probability of creating very first coloring style of the project, see console for the hidden feature)

metadata.name: Sketch B #47
metadata.description:
Sketch is an open-ended series. Works evolve as I code a generative project, sometimes drastically. Intermediate works usually don't see the light of day - they get archived and forgotten. This series is snapshots of different forms along the way - each standing alone, but also part of a larger meandering work flow. The word Sketch implies incompleteness. This project may end up being two works, or it could evolve for years. Part of the joy of generative art is never knowing what's around the corner. I have no set schedule. There may be multiple Sketches released a week, or it could be weeks or months between drops. I have no idea where Sketch is heading and there is no guarantee of cohesiveness from Sketch to Sketch. Color palettes and forms will change as new ideas are explored.

Sketch B remains simple. The basic grid of Sketch A is there, but is starting to be filled. Grid lines are trimmed as if sketched. Colors continue to be borrowed from Echos/Orbits and new colors from Bent are incorporated. Grid size, padding, line thickness, fill color, and fill percentage and patterns vary.
